2025 Member Choice Awards: Best Cruise Lines Overall

By Brooke Franco
  • Share
  • Tweet
  • Pin It
  • Print

The 2025 Member Choice Awards for Best Cruise Lines recognizes the top cruise brands that stood out to our community members for their overall experience in the past year. These awards highlight cruise lines with the highest overall review rating across all their ships. This year's honorees stand out for providing exceptional vacations and setting new standards in the world of cruising.

 

While many of these cruise lines are returning winners, their rankings have slightly changed in a few categories over the past year. In our list of the Best Cruise Lines, we break down the top honors across four types of cruise experience: mainstream, Premium, Luxury, and River. The respective lines are also listed in these categories on our site. 

The 2025 Member Choice Award winners for the best overall cruise lines are:

Best Mainstream Cruise Line

  1. Royal Caribbean - 4.38
  2. Celebrity Cruises - 4.327
  3. Princess Cruises - 4.248
  4. Holland America Line - 4.241
  5. Carnival Cruise Line - 4.236
Honorable Mention: Virgin Voyages - 4.22

Once again, Royal Caribbean took top honors as our best mainstream cruise line for the year. Royal Caribbean has held this title and number one position in the 2022, 2023, and 2024 Member Choice Awards, and it once again keeps its ‘crown’ receiving recognition for 2025. 

Year after year, Royal Caribbean is our members’ top pick as the line that stood out the most among its peers for unforgettable guest experiences and onboard ship quality. This reinforces Royal Caribbean’s reputation as an industry leader, committed to customer satisfaction and delivering a superior product in all aspects of creating a memorable cruise vacation. 

Community member alexkauf shared this feedback in their review of a Royal Caribbean vacation, “Our cruise was an amazing experience, highlighted by exceptional service, delightful dining, and unforgettable moments created by the warm and friendly staff. We enjoyed exploring beautiful destinations while relaxing on a well-appointed ship. The entire journey was a perfect blend of adventure and luxury.”

Celebrity Cruises remained number two for the best overall mainstream cruise line. In the past year, it consistently received high scores for its excellent cruise experience. Princess Cruises came in third in the best mainstream line category, rising in the ranks with excellent review feedback after being absent from the list in our 2023 and 2024 awards. With just a small percentage point in scoring difference, we must recognize Princess for the exceptional overall guest experience reported by our community members. 

Community member suzanscott2013 shared this gloating review of their Princess Cruises voyage, “This was our 21st cruise, many of them with Princess, and one our top five favorites! The ship was very, very comfortable, the ports were super, the staff friendly and professional, and most of all the peaceful and restful vacation we needed.” 

Holland America Line remained our number four best mainstream cruise line, with Carnival Cruise Line just a few points behind in spot five. Each of these top mainstream line’s rankings highlights its commitment to offering memorable voyages, excellent service, and diverse amenities. 

Brooke will add 2-3 sentences here on Virgin Voyages as honorable mention - referencing close scores to the top listed, fewer ships for members to review, and thoughts on how we anticipate the line to grow in the list in future years.  

Explore Royal Caribbean Cruises
 

 

Best Premium Cruise Line

  1. Viking Ocean Cruises - 4.44
  2. Windstar Cruises - 4.417
  3. Azamara Cruises - 4.332
  4. Cunard - 4.323
  5. Oceania Cruises - 4.257

The Best Premium Cruise Line category ranks the brands offering just that ‘little bit extra’ in service levels, attention to detail, and ship amenities. You will typically find that the lines in this category have smaller ships and higher fares than mainstream lines. However, these brands offer many inclusions in their pricing, like airfare, onboard credits, drinks, and other amenities you commonly have to pay extra for with a mainstream line cruise. 

The same cruise lines usually make the top five for this category, with slight shifts in the rankings depending on how many members choose to sail with each line and rate their experience by writing a review. However, the overall scores are consistently very close, with just tenths of points separating all these cruise lines. 

Viking Ocean Cruises rose from third place last year to our winner for the best premium cruise line of 2025. The cruise line consistently ranks highly for its exceptional service, enrichment-focused onboard programming, and variety of destination-focused itineraries worldwide. Viking Ocean Cruises operates fourteen ships, all of which accommodate just 930 passengers each.  

Community member CruisingNinja2 shared this about their 2024 Viking Ocean Cruise’ Viking Jupiter, “Quite simply the best ocean cruise experience I've had. The itinerary is magical, the ship is sublime, the staff is top notch and the shore excursions are curated for ‘the thinking person’. Viking is on the top of its game.”

Last year’s number one winner Windstar Cruises, dropped to second place for this year, just a mere hundredths of a point behind Viking. Windstar features a fleet of elegantly designed small sailing yachts and all-suite motor yachts and a boutique cruise experience that allows for access to smaller ports in lesser-traveled locales. 

“This ship and this itinerary offered a marvelous way to experience French Polynesia. The beauty of the islands, the warmth of the locals, the elegance and comfort of the vessel, and superb ship's staff are a combination for a perfect vacation,” remarked community member Rosende in a review of their cruise on Windstar’s Star Breeze. 

Azamara Cruises was in third place in the premium category, which dropped from number two last year. Cunard and Oceania Cruises retained their spots, ranked fourth and fifth, respectively for the category. Of note, we received more reviews for these two lines than any others in the category. The scores were all incredibly close for these premium lines, with mere tenths or hundredths of a point separating the lines. No matter which of these lines you choose for a vacation, you are in for a treat of pampering service and exquisite dining while onboard comfortable and beautifully appointed ships.

All Voyages from Viking Ocean Cruises 

Best Luxury Cruise Line 

  1. Regent Seven Seas Cruises - 4.274
  2. Seabourn - 4.268
  3. Silversea Cruises - 4.246
  4. Crystal - 4.22

Many of our community members enjoyed a taste of the high life by sailing onboard several luxury lines this past year. In this category, you find brands that offer superb onboard service, exceptional dining, spacious suites, and personalized touches like a dedicated butler for your voyage. 

Our 2025 Best Luxury Cruise Line winner is Regent Seven Seas Cruises, which rose from number two in the category last year. Regent offers an ultra-premium onboard experience, with inclusive amenities, all-suite accommodations (99% of which have a balcony), and some of the lowest crew-to-guest ratios in the industry. 

“We had a wonderful cruise. We were fortunate to have perfect weather, excellent food, great service from the crew, a wonderful butler, and outstanding entertainment, particularly for a ship of this relatively small size,” shared community member rstalljr in a review of their cruise on Regent’s Seven Seas Splendor. 

Coming in at number two was Seaborn, which was last year’s winner of this category. The review points only separated it from reclaiming its title by just a hundredth of a point. Silversea once again came in at number three for best luxury line, and number four was Crystal. This was the first full year of review data we received since the Crystal brand was re-introduced to the market following its purchase by A&K Travel Group Ltd. We look forward to seeing how Crystal performs in the years ahead in this category with its plans to introduce new ships to the market. 

We must note that several cruise lines received honorable mentions in the Best Luxury Cruise Line category this year: Ponant, SeaDream Yacht Club, and the Ritz-Carlton Yacht Collection. These brands all scored very highly in our review rankings this year; however, we received fewer overall reviews, thus eliminating them from being judged for the category as a whole. 

See All Regent Seven Seas Cruises Voyages
 

 

Best River Cruise Line

  1. Viking River Cruises - 4.45
  2. Avalon Waterways - 4.418
  3. AmaWaterways - 4.398
  4. American Cruise Line - 4.379
  5. Uniworld River Cruises - 4.363

River cruises offer a unique experience for travelers to see both small villages and larger, well-known cities in a unique, highly personalized environment. You will find most river cruises in Europe, with some brands offering voyages on U.S. waterways and far-off locales in South America, Egypt, and Asia. The segment is rapidly growing year over year, and in 2025 had more community reviews submitted for river cruise lines than ever before.  

Once again, our top five river cruise line winners for 2025 remained the same as last year, with a few changes in the lineup. Once again, Viking River Cruises was our member’s pick for the year's best overall river cruise line. The cruise brand is one of the most prominent names in river cruising, with exceptional itineraries, enriching onboard programming, and small, well-thought-out vessels designed to traverse the boutique waterways. 

Community member JGA3 shared the following about their Viking River Cruise vacation, “The Viking River Cruise was amazing!! We highly recommend this cruise to anyone interested in European history and beautiful architecture. The Viking staff could not have been any more friendly, knowledgeable, and professional.”

Avalon Waterways jumped up in the 2025 rankings from four to two this year for best river cruise brands, while AmaWaterways moved up from four to three. U.S.-based cruise operator American Cruise Line dropped from second to fourth in very close ratings. Uniworld River Cruises kept its spot at number five in this category, with just a tiny percentage point behind American Cruise Line.  

All the scores for these brands were very close, and there was a record-setting number of reviews, indicating that more travelers chose to sail European river vacations, travel further from home, and love everything about their river cruise experience.

7 Things That Are Only Acceptable on a Cruise

By Thomas Faddegon and Simon Duvall
  • Share
  • Tweet
  • Pin It
  • Print

Cruising is the only vacation where you can spend the day exploring a new destination and your nights enjoying top-notch entertainment and cuisine, only to wake up in another port to do it all over again. But there also some smaller, more subtle things you can do on a cruise that you can’t really get away with anywhere else.

1. Ordering 3 entrees for dinner and taking only a few bites from each.

This is what your main dining room table should look like. - Photo by Shutterstock.com

At Sea: No one notices or cares — you’re an experienced cruiser who knows how to get your money’s worth. Order at least a couple appetizers while you’re at it.

On Land: Your waiter will give you a weird look, and you’ll feel the judgmental glances from the surrounding tables for the duration of your meal. Plus it can get really expensive, really quickly.

 

2. Not carrying a purse, wallet, or your keys for days at a time.

It's hard to imagine leaving home without these essentials. - Photo by Thinkstock.com

At Sea: Your cruise card pays for everything and opens your cabin door, so everything you need is around your neck on a lanyard or tucked in your pocket.

On Land: Noticing you don’t have your purse or wallet will probably give you a small panic attack after it dawns on you that you can’t pay for anything. Oh, and you’re probably locked out of your house too.

 

3. Wearing a swimsuit & sandals just about anywhere.

Completely acceptable cruise ship attire. - Photo by Shutterstock.com

At Sea: You won’t get seated at formal dinner (although most cruise lines have been relaxing their dress codes lately, so who knows) but you won’t have a problem on most of the ship.

On Land: The further you get away from the beach, the more people will look at you like you’re completely crazy.

 

4. Turning off your cell phone and not checking social media.

You don't see this screen very often, do you? - Photo by Shutterstock.com

At Sea: Cruising is one of the few getaways where you can still go off the grid. For those who love to disconnect, this excuse will be harder to use as cruise ship WiFi becomes faster and faster, but for now, you can still get away with leaving your phone in your cabin.

On Land: If you don’t answer your phone for a couple of days, your friends & family might alert the police and launch a search and rescue mission.

 

 

 

5. Staying in a room without a window.

It's not often you see a bed in a windowless room. - Photo by Celebrity Cruises

At Sea: You’re a frugal cruiser who only uses your cabin for the three S’s — sleeping, showering and well, you know…— so you don’t mind living in what’s essentially a large walk-in closet for a week.

On Land: You’re broke or living in New York City (which is kind of redundant).

 

6. Packing your own alcohol, soda, or water in your luggage.

Bringing your own water is not as crazy as it sounds. - Photo by iStock

At Sea: Bringing your own drinks on board is a tried and true method of saving money on a beverage package. Lines do have different rules and regulations about what can be brought aboard, so it’s worth checking before you lug that case of bottled water to the cruise port.

On Land: Anyone who sees your bag will think you have a serious alcohol or soda addiction, or an irrational fear of your plane crashing in the middle of a desert. And good luck getting that vodka past the TSA screener.

 

7. Eating room service breakfast, breakfast, morning snack, lunch, second lunch, afternoon snack, dinner, and midnight snack. All in one day.

This is a typical cruise ship "snack". - Photo by Carnival

At Sea: The idea of “three square meals a day” goes right out the window on a cruise. Everyone else is doing the same thing, so no one is going to bat an eye at your afternoon snack, which could very well be a full burger with extra fries. Don’t worry, be happy.

On Land: If you try and continue this habit on land, it won’t be long before your friends organize an intervention or gift you a Weight Watchers membership.

What is a Cruise Roll Call?

By Kimberly Coyne
  • Share
  • Tweet
  • Pin It
  • Print

Whether you’re an outgoing social butterfly who can’t wait to start meeting your fellow passengers or the shy type who would feel more comfortable knowing a few people prior to sailing, signing up for a cruise ship roll call allows you to get to know people on your cruise while your feet are still on dry land. Learn more about roll calls:

 

1. What exactly is a cruise roll call? 

Technically, it's a forum thread for passengers on the same sailing. Think of it as a shared message board: Boards are broken down by ship and sail date, so the only people on the thread will be passengers you'll be sailing with on your cruise.

2. Is it just for meeting other people?

Nope, it's way more than that. Cruise ship roll calls are also a great source of information. For those who’ve never stepped foot on a ship, it’s an excellent opportunity to ask more experienced cruisers questions before the sailing. And even if it’s not your first cruise, it never hurts to ask those in the know for recommendations on everything from restaurants to shore excursions.

A roll call is a great planning tool for travelers who like to plan in advance. If, for example, you’d rather go scuba diving with friends than strangers, there’s no need to wait to see if you meet fellow divers on the ship — see if any are in your roll call. Some tours also offer discounted rates for groups, so bringing other travelers along can save you money. 

3. How do I join a roll call?

You can join roll calls on Cruiseline.com, but we've focused on optimizing the experience on our app, Shipmate. You'll get push notifications when someone replies to your question, and you can even send direct messages to other cruisers on your sailing. All you have to do is download the app, sign up for an account, then go to "My Cruises," select "Add Cruise," and find your ship and sailing. Once you have it, then click "Add Cruise." 

4. What can you do in a roll call?

If you have a burning question about anything from drink packages to shore excursions, go ahead and ask it. If you don't have a question, simply sign in and introduce yourself. It's not a bad idea to add a little about what you like to do and whom you’re traveling with since couples, families, and single cruisers will often look for different things on a cruise. Be sure to check your roll call often in case you can help answer other fellow passengers' questions and see what's new.
